# ESP32-Smart-Environmental-Alert-Node 

2 Notes:
Note (1) = THIS IS AN EXPANSION OF ESP32-LOCAL-SENSOR-NODE
Note (2) = This is the same as the dual mode switch, but the only difference is 
that the dual mode switch just toggles between Uptime and Sensor info and with the dual sensor Mode 
depends on how long you press the button before it switches to he other Mode.


It has a button that does different things depending on how long you hold it short press shows "Button pressed!" on the display, 
long press switches to an info screen with IP address and uptime. 
No delay() used anywhere, everything runs on millis().

| ![Setup](images/setup.jpg) | ![OLED](images/oled.jpg)

---

## ✨ Features

- 🌡️ Measures temperature and humidity using a BME280 sensor  
- 🖥️ Displays live data on an SSD1306 OLED screen (128x64)  
- 📶 Creates its own WiFi hotspot (`MijnESP32`)  
- 🌐 Local web server at `http://192.168.4.1`  
- ♻️ Auto-refreshes every 2 seconds (via JavaScript)  
- ⚠️ Error handling for sensor failures or loose connections  
- 🔒 No sensitive data in main code.  
- 🧠 Non-blocking timing with `millis()` → web server stays responsive
- 🖱️ Interactive button:
  - **While pressed**: shows device IP address and uptime  
  - **Automaticely(after 5 sec)*: returns to live temperature and humidity readings
- 🌡️ Smart alert system: Reacts to high temperature with LED, OLED, and web feedback. 

---

> ⚠️ **Why no `°` symbol?**  
> The `Adafruit_SSD1306` library has limited support for special characters like the degree symbol (`°`). To keep the code simple and reliable for beginners, the OLED displays only `"C"` instead of `"°C"`.  
>   
> ✅ The **web version** (in your browser) **does show** the correct `°C` symbol thanks to HTML encoding.

This is a common limitation in embedded displays — not a bug!

## 🧰 Components Required

- ESP32 Development Board (e.g., ESP32 DevKit)
- BME280 temperature/humidity sensor (I²C)
- SSD1306 OLED display (128x64, I²C)
- Breadboard and jumper wires
- Micro-USB cable
- RED LED
- 2x 220 Ohm Resistor
- 1x pushbutton

## How It Works
The device runs in **Sensor Mode** by default.  
Press and hold the button to enter **Info Mode**, which displays:
- IP address (`Your IP-adress`)  
- Uptime (formatted as `Xm Ys` since boot)

Release the button to return immediately to Sensor Mode.

---

## 🔌 Wiring (I²C Bus)

Both sensors share the same I²C pins (button added):

| ESP32 Pin | Function | Connected To        |
|----------|----------|--------------------- |
| 3.3V     | Power    | VCC of BME280 + OLED |
| GND      | Ground   | GND of BME280 + OLED + Button(one side) |
| GPIO21   | SDA      | SDA of BME280 + OLED |
| GPIO22   | SCL      | SCL of BME280 + OLED |
| GPIO4    | Input    | Button(other side)   |

Note: The button is connected between GPIO 4 and GND. The code enables the internal pull-up resistor, so no external resistor is required.


> 💡 Ensure both devices use **different I²C addresses** (BME280: `0x76`, OLED: `0x3C`).

---

## ▶️ Usage

1. **Install required libraries** in Arduino IDE:  
   - `Adafruit BME280 Library`  
   - `Adafruit SSD1306`  
   - `Adafruit GFX Library`

> 2. Create `secrets.h` by copying `secrets.h.example` to `secrets.h`, then edit the values:
> ```bash
> cp secrets.h.example secrets.h
> ```

> Open `secrets.h` and replace `"MijnESP32"` and `"12345678"` with your WiFi name and password.
